# Cursor Rules Format

## Core Structure

Write rules in this format:

```mdc
---
description: USE WHEN [TRIGGER] to [OUTCOME]
globs: src/**/*.{ts,tsx}
alwaysApply: false
---

# Rule Title

## Context

- When to apply
- Prerequisites or conditions

## Requirements

- Concise, testable, actionable items

## Examples

<example type="valid">
  Valid example with a brief explanation.
</example>

<example type="invalid">
  Invalid example with a short explanation.
</example>
```

## File Organization

### Location

Store rules in a subdirectory of `.cursor/rules/` as `.mdc` files based on rule type.

Subdirectory structure:

- `.cursor/rules/meta/`: Creating Cursor rules and other AI instructions
- `.cursor/rules/core/`: Fundamental instructions for how AI agents must behave
- `.cursor/rules/languages/`: Specific programming languages
- `.cursor/rules/languages/typescript/`
- `.cursor/rules/frameworks/`: Specific frameworks
- `.cursor/rules/conventions/`: Project conventions and patterns
- `.cursor/rules/testing/`: Testing standards
- `.cursor/rules/workflow/`: Workflows

### Private Rules (git-ignored)

- File name MUST begin with an underscore (`_my-private-rule.mdc`)

### Glob Patterns

Use standard glob patterns:

- Cursor Rules: `.cursor/rules/**/*.mdc`
- Language: `src/**/*.{js,ts,tsx}`
- Testing: `**/*.test.{ts,tsx}`
- React Components: `src/**/*.tsx`
- Docs: `docs/**/*.md`
- Multiple Extensions: `src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}`
- Multiple Files: `dist/**/*, docs/**/*.md`

## Required Fields

### Frontmatter

- `description`: USE WHEN [TRIGGER] to [OUTCOME] format, under 120 characters
  - Use gerund-style trigger phrases (e.g., "creating...", "refactoring...")
- `globs`: Standard glob pattern (no quotes)
- `alwaysApply`: Boolean (usually false)

### Body

- Context: Define usage conditions
- Requirements: List actionable, testable items
- Examples: Show concise valid and invalid rule examples

## Formatting Guidelines

- Keep rules short and precise
- Use inline backticks and code blocks; no excess markdown
- Allowed XML tags: `<danger>`, `<required>`, `<critical>`, `<example type="valid">`, `<example type="invalid">`
- Indent XML tag content by 2 spaces
- Use Mermaid syntax to simplify complex rules
- Use emojis if they improve clarity: ❌ (invalid, bad), ✅ (valid, good)
- Write instructions for LLM processing, not human discussion

## AI Optimization

- Use imperative language
- No intro to list points
- Write precise, deterministic "USE WHEN [TRIGGER] to [OUTCOME]" descriptions
- Provide minimal valid/invalid examples
- Optimize for AI context window efficiency: remove redundancy
- Use standard glob patterns without quotes (`*.js`, `src/**/*.ts`)

## AI Context Efficiency

- Keep frontmatter concise
- Limit examples to essential patterns
- Use clear hierarchy
- Remove redundancy
- Focus on machine-actionable instructions
- Maintain high information density with minimal tokens
- Keep the rules file under 500 lines; if not possible, ask user how to narrow the rule scope

<critical>
  - NEVER include verbose explanations or redundant context
  - Keep the file as short as possible without sacrificing rule impact
  - Frontmatter must only include `description`, `globs`, and `alwaysApply`
</critical>
